Unfortunately, many meetings are now held differently, and it has long been forgotten the promise of a "kinder and gentler" policy, if it has ever been remembered.
It is increasingly clear that there is no tolerance for dissenting views in the Labour Party; each opinion is judged to be in line with the party leadership.
It all started not long after Jeremy Corbyn took office, and colleagues who seemed to me to have similar views began to expect me to change direction and take positions that I would not have agreed with before, such as national security or the EU single market.
After every public appearance – regardless of the content – I meet on social media with attacks calling for the nomination to be received, for the condemnation of centrism or for leaving the Labour Party.
This is not just my experience.
I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the remarks directed at me are rather political in nature.
I admire the professionalism and determination of colleagues who experience sexist or racist treatment on a daily basis, but do not shy away from further action.
One of the most disappointing aspects of current policy is moving to the agenda with insulting others.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn stated that the Labour Party should support a culture of tolerance.
In fact, we are no longer a group of people with different views. With each motion for a "vot of no confidence" and each change in the party's rules of choice, the party's worldview is narrowed.
Over the past two years, I have been repeatedly advised not to lean out and to keep quiet on certain issues.
But that's not why I went into politics.
Since joining the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student as a result of the negligence of Margaret Thatcher's government, which led to the dissolution of my school class, I have been trying to ensure a better quality of public services for those in need – both as a local councillor and minister.
I never covered my beliefs, not even during the last election campaign.
Everyone in the Nottingham East district knew my position and knew about the differences of opinion with the party authorities.
To those who supported the proposal on Friday, I wish to say that I cannot understand the desire to waste time and energy on the question of my loyalty to the Labour leader in the face of an upcoming Brexit that will harm households, businesses and public services.
The most important message, however, is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents (both members of the Labour Party and others): I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threats of rescinding nominations or ad hoc political goals will deter me from acting in accordance with my beliefs and in the best interests of all of you.
Chris Leslie is a Member of Parliament for Nottingham East
