"The sea belongs to us": deprived of access to the sea Bolivia hopes that the court will reopen its path to the Pacific
Sailors patrol the vicinity of the naval base in La Paz.
There are blue flags flying from public buildings.
In the naval ports from Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the motto is: "The sea is ours by law.
It is our duty to recover it."
In Bolivia's non-accessible sea, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources from the 19th century is still alive, as if dreaming of sailing again in the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps the greatest in decades. Bolivia is awaiting the verdict of the International Court of Justice. It is due to be issued on October 1 after a five-year trial.
"Bolivia's actions are gaining momentum. Residents are unanimous, optimistic and are counting on a favorable verdict," said Bolivian diplomat Roberto Calzadilla.
Many Bolivians across the country will watch the meeting of the International Court of Justice together, hoping that an organization based in The Hague will recognize Bolivia's claim and after decades of fruitless talks, Chile will have to enter into negotiations to grant the state independent access to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic president, who will face a controversial re-election battle next year, also puts his hope in Monday's ruling.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific," he vowed at the end of August.
However, some analysts say that the chances of a favorable ruling for Bolivia are slim and that even a favorable decision would not make much difference.
The United Nations, based in The Hague, has no authority to grant Bolivia the territory of Chile, and has also stipulated that it will not affect the arrangements for possible talks.
As the Chilean International Law Specialist, Paz Zorate, said, the decision of the International Court of Justice would be made six months after the final arguments were put forward. Such a short time shows that the case "was not complicated".
Unfortunately for Bolivia, the last four years may have distanced the country from its goal.
"The issue of access to the sea has been appropriated by the current Bolivian administration," said Paz Zurate.
Morales' relentless rhetoric deprived the Chileans of any remaining goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but this will be very difficult in the face of the situation.
For both of these countries, there has been no exchange of ambassadors since 1962.
Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, former president and Bolivian representative in The Hague, disagreed with the opinion that the court's decision-making process was extremely fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia "a unique opportunity to start a new era in relations with Chile" and the opportunity to "end a 139-year period of disputes with mutual benefit", he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, was using the topic of access to the sea as part of political play.
"Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The ruling is an excellent opportunity to see that we need to deal with the past."
