John Edward: Language skills essential for the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland are constantly enjoying their academic achievements – in 2018 they were able to boast further excellent exam results, supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social endeavors.
Represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), schools attended by more than 30,000 students across Scotland aim to provide the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career path, and to indicate their role as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector with the ability to develop and implement a curriculum tailored to the needs of the school, we see that modern languages are still popular and desirable subjects to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to another man in a language he understands, then it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
This is a clear reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The results of the last exam this year show that languages are ranked first in league rankings, with the highest pass rates occurring in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages received a higher grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students scored higher A in Mandarin, and 72 percent of German learners, 69 percent of French learners, and 63 percent of Spanish learners also scored A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, language learning, as electives, is conducted in the same scope as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) within curricula in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 study by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that employers' lack of language skills was responsible for 17 percent of job vacancies.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity to prepare young people to start their careers.
These skills are essential in a globalised world with a growing number of jobs requiring language skills,
A lifelong skill, like learning a second language, will provide a huge advantage in the future, regardless of your career path.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically increases the chances of a multilingual person in relation to the competition.
According to a YouGov poll in 2013, which involved more than 4,000 British adults, 75% of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only language with a double-digit percentage of speakers, i.e. 15%.
Therefore, investing in foreign language teaching is so important for today's children.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular the languages of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding suitable employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ in terms of the languages taught in it.
Many schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of the child, there will always be many languages to choose from in independent schools, which will be taught by teaching staff specialized in this area.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed – regardless of what the future holds for them.
At present, it cannot be denied that in the international business environment languages are still crucial for the future of the country, and so this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be treated as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer Scottish youth ample choice, diversity and level.
That's just the way it should be.
John Edward, Chairman, Scottish Council of Independent Schools
