North Korea says no to unilateral disarmament without confidence.
North Korea's foreign minister said on Saturday during a speech at the UN that the failure to lift sanctions only exacerbates North Korea's lack of confidence in the United States and there is no way that the country would unilaterally give up nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho said at the annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" last year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and a commitment to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see any concrete response from the US," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there will be no guarantee of our national security and under such circumstances, there will be no unilateral disarmament of North Korea."
While Ri reiterated known North Korean complaints about Washington's reluctance to take a "gradual" approach to denuclearization, under which North Korea would be rewarded for taking gradual action, his statement appeared to be significant because it did not reject unilateral denuclearization as it had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between the incumbent President of the United States and the leader of North Korea, held on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim Jong Un pledged to work towards the "denuclarization of the Korean peninsula" and Trump promised guarantees of North Korea's security.
North Korea expected a formal end to the Korean War (between 1950 and 1953), but the United States delegation announced that Pyongyang must first give up nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted calls to ease severe international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States insists on 'denuclarization in the first place' and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the signing of an 'end-of-war declaration'," Ri said.
"The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is the dreams of people who behave ignorantly towards us.
The problem, however, is that the failure to lift sanctions deepens our distrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, which was discussed earlier this week by the U.S. leader at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister pointed out three meetings between Kim Jong Un and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, after which he added: "If the party to the denuclearization issue was South Korea and not the United States, then there was no such deadlock in the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula."
Mim this, the tone of Ri's speech was completely different compared to last year, when he said during the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korea's missiles in U.S. territory is inevitable after "Mr Evil President" Trump called Kim Jong Un a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
This year at a UN forum, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim Jong Un for his courage in taking steps to disarm, but also said much work needed to be put in, and said that until North Korea was stripped of its nuclear weapons, sanctions would not be lifted.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had not set a time frame for it, saying, "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia say the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said Thursday at the U.N. Security Council that: "The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue and be continuous until we find full, final and verified denuclearization."
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea in an attempt to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear program and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said later that he would visit Pyongyang again next month in preparation for the second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit cannot be called a success.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying that progress had been made, after which North Korea denounced him for "setting gangster demands" within hours.
North Korea pledged this month at a meeting with Moon Jae-in that it would dismantle the missile testing site and the nuclear complex if the United States took "appropriate measures."
He stated that Kim Jong Un told him that the "adequate measures" he cared about were security guarantees Trump had pledged in Singapore and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on proper long rest
A new course at Harvard University, held this year, provided all students with more sleep to combat the growing macho culture of learning by "caffeinated all-night students."
Academic students from the best university in the world often have no idea about the basics of taking care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create a course by giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on science.
"After the speech, one girl came up to me and said, 'Why are you telling me this only now that I'm in my senior year of college?'
She stated that no one had ever told her the meaning of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
During the course, which took place for the first time this year, students are explained how good sleep habits help to achieve good results in science and sports, as well as improve the overall well-being of students.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health service, said that the course was decided to introduce after it was found that students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a range of interactive assignments.
One section includes an image of a dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, exercises, and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light, and how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, as well as how important it is to maintain sleep regularity.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routine.
"We know that this will not cause an immediate change in student behavior.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as everyone has a right to know the health effects of cigarette smoking," added Professor Czeisler.
A culture of pride from "all-night learning" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students means an increasing problem of lack of sleep.
Providing enough good quality sleep should be a "secret weapon" for students to combat stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even avoid weight gain, as lack of sleep causes the brain to go into starvation mode, making the student constantly hungry," he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push for the introduction of a course for the entire campus.
The next step according to him is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar degree program before moving on to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set up a reminder alert when they need to go to bed and when they need to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted by electronic device screens and LED lighting, which can upset the circadian rhythm and lead to trouble falling asleep.
