Almanac: inventor of the Geiger counter
And now the page from our edition of Almanac's Sunday Morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago... the day the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity that eventually led to the creation of a device known as a Geiger counter.
Since then, Geiger's counter has become both an element of science and pop culture, such as in the 1950 film Bells of Coronado, which starred these seemingly unlikely cowboy-scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "This is a Geiger counter that is used to locate radioactive minerals such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you will hear the effects of atoms emitted by radioactive minerals."
Evans: "Now you hear something!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name has survived to this day.
A new cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to "see" enemy cells.
New cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to "see" enemy cells and destroy them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize hostile cells as part of treatment.
This method involves separating immune cells from the patient and changing them in the laboratory.
Then they can "see" the protein common to many cancers. Then they are re-injected into the body.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
One woman treated with a vaccine teaching the immune system to recognize hostile cells has been reported to have ovarian cancer atrophy for more than 18 months.
The method involves separating immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers called HER2, and then re-injecting the patient with these cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that this vaccine is very promising."
HER2 "drives the growth of several types of cancer", including breast, ovarian, lung and colon cancer, explained Prof. Berzofsky.
A similar approach of taking immune cells from patients and "teaching" their localization of cancer cells worked to treat some type of leukemia.
