HIV/Aids: China reports 14 percent increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and suffering from AIDS.
More than 820,000 people are affected by this problem, as reported by the country's health workers.
About 40,000 new cases were reported in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases were sexually transmitted, meaning a change from the past.
Traditionally, the HIV virus spreads rapidly in parts of China as a result of a transfusion of infected blood.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been almost completely reduced, as Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, compared to a year ago, the number of people living with HIV and suffering from AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is a serious problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is widespread.
Given the country's conservative values, studies estimate that 70-90% of men who have sex with men will eventually marry a woman.
Many cases of disease transmission are due to insufficient protection when having sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has provided universal access to HIV drugs as part of efforts to combat this problem.
Maxine Waters denies that one of her team members leaked the Republican Party's senators' data - these are "dangerous lies" and "conspiracy theories".
A member of the U.S. House of Representatives, Maxine Waters, on Saturday denied allegations that a member of her team had posted the personal details of three Republican senators on Wikipedia's respective legislators.
A member of the Los Angeles Democratic Party assured that these accusations were made by experts and websites linked to "ultra-right wing".
"Lies, lies and even more despicable lies," Waters said in a statement on Twitter.
Public information reportedly included home addresses and phone numbers of U.S. Senators Lindsey Graham of South Carolina and Mike Lee and Orrin Hatch of Utah.
It was posted on the Internet on Thursday by an unknown person on Capitol Hill during a panel hearing in the Senate on allegations of sexual misconduct against Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh.
The leak came some time after three senators challenged Kavanaugh's candidacy.
Conservative parties such as Gateway Pundit and RedState reported that the IP address identifying the source of the posts was linked to the Waters office and published information regarding a Waters team member, according to Hill.
"This unsubstantiated allegation is completely false, and it's a 100 percent lie," Waters continued.
"A member of my team – whose identity, personal data and safety were compromised as a result of these fraudulent and false allegations – was in no way responsible for the leaking of this information.
This unsubstantiated allegation is completely false, and it is a 100 percent lie."
Waters' statement quickly sparked criticism on the Internet, including from Ari Fleischer, a former White House press secretary.
"Such a way of denying is wrong," Fleischer wrote.
"This suggests that she does not have the right temperament to be a member of Congress.
When someone is accused of something they haven't done, they can't be angry.
He can't provoke.
He must not question the motives of the person making the charges.
For that, he must remain calm."
Fleischer seemed to compare Waters' reaction to the Democratic criticism of Judge Kavanaugh, who was accused of showing excessive anger during Thursday's hearing.
Omar Navarro, a Republican candidate running for the midterm election to replace Waters, also voiced his thoughts on Twitter.
"It's a big deal, if it's true," he tweeted.
In her statement, Waters said her cabinet had notified "the relevant authorities and law enforcement agencies of these fraudulent accusations."
"The perpetrators will be exposed and held legally accountable for all their actions that pose a threat to any member of my team," she said.
Johnny English: Knockout Movie Review – A Spy Parody with Weakened Rowan Atkinson
Searching for references to Brexit in every new film with a British thread has already become the norm. This seems to apply to the new part of the series of action and comedy films "Johnny English", which began in 2003 with the film "Johnny English" and which returned to cinema screens in 2011 with the film "Johnny English: Reactivation".
Will a self-speak satire about how hopeless we are become the country's new export commodity?
In any case, the ever-surprised, rubber-faced, incompetent Johnny English was once again licensed to babble – his name more than anything else signals that he is an elaborate, comical product intended for non-English audiences.
He is, of course, a silly secret agent who, despite his bizarre taste for smoothie glamour, has a touch of Inspector Clouseau, a pinch of Beans, and a cap of that guy adding one note to the theme tune of the Chariots of Fire at the opening ceremony of the 2012 London Olympics.
In the past, he was also a traveler and a world-class mystery man – Atkinson once played in the already forgotten television commercials Barclaycard, in which he left chaos behind.
There is one or two notable moments in Johnny English's latest film series.
I loved the scene where Johnny English was approaching the helicopter, dressed in medieval armor, while his helmet was rhythmically hit by the rotor blades.
The screen clearly shows Atkinson's gift to physically play comedy, but the sense of humor seems to be quite low-flying and unnecessary, especially since now also "serious" film brands such as 007 and Mission Impossible offer comedic elements as part of the film.
The humorous elements seem to be aimed at children rather than adults – in my opinion Johnny English's crazy adventures are not as imaginative and consistent as the gags in Atkinson's silent films about Jasi Beans.
The ever-present assumption is that Britain is in serious trouble.
Cyberhacker penetrates the UK's super-secret spy network, revealing the identity of all British agents operating in the field, much to the horror of the agent on duty, Kevin Eldon, who unfortunately played a minor role.
