Her intelligence advisors inform her that due to the disclosure of the identity of all active spies she will have to reinstate one of the retired agents.
And that means the inept Johnny English himself, now employed as a teacher at some classy school, giving unofficial lessons on how to become a secret agent – some pretty good gags when giving English spying lessons.
English is called to Whitehall for briefing, reconnecting with his former sidekick Bough, played again by Ben Miller.
Bough is now a married man associated with the submarine commander, a cheerful but somewhat tired character played by Vicki Pepperdine.
Thus, Batman and Robin partridge in Her Majesty's secret service return to action, meeting the beautiful femme fatale Ophelia Bulletova, a character played by Olga Kurylenko.
Meanwhile, the prime minister is dangerously overpowered by a charismatic tech billionaire who claims to be able to solve Britain's computer problems – the ominous Jason Volta, played by Jake Lacy.
English and Bough begin their crusade of absurd situations: disguised as waiters set fire to a French restaurant; bring chaos by sneaking aboard a luxury yacht Volta; and English wreaks havoc when using a virtual reality kit to get acquainted with the interior of Volta's house.
In the latter sequence, all restrictions disappear, however, despite the nice and boisterous performance, the entire film closely resembles children's television.
Typical average.
As with other Johnny English films, I couldn't help but think: can't the British film industry give Rowan Atkinson a role that really suits his talent?
