What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it helped to reduce poverty in any way?
This Saturday in New York City, the Global Citizen Festival will be held, an annual music event that boasts an extremely impressive line-up of performing stars and an equally impressive mission – the eradication of poverty in the world.
The 7th Global Citizen Festival will visit tens of thousands of people coming to Great Lawn in Central Park to not only enjoy the performances of stars like Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also to support the achievement of the event's most important goal of eradicating extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which started in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international group of anti-poverty activists by increasing the number of people actively fighting against it.
To receive a free ticket to the event (unless it was decided to purchase a VIP ticket), concert participants had to complete a number of tasks or "actions", such as volunteering, sending an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or other significant activities to help raise awareness of the goal of poverty eradication.
But what successes can Global Citizen boast in the perspective of the 12 years remaining to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding people with a free concert a good way to convince them to require action, or is it another case of so-called "clictimism" when people feel they are doing something important by signing an online petition or posting an entry on Tweeter?
Global Citizen claims that since 2011, it has recorded over 19 million "actions" by people supporting the action, aiming to achieve many different goals.
He also claims that these actions helped spur world leaders to announce commitments and laws worth more than $37 billion that are expected to affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 commitments and announcements resulting from its activities, under which at least $10 billion has already been paid or financed.
The group estimates that the secured measures have so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people worldwide.
Some of the key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK partnership of investors and implementers committed to "helping children reach their full potential", which promised to give Rwanda $35 million to help address malnutrition in the country, after members of Global Citizen sent over 4,700 tweets.
"With the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and members of the Global Citizen like you, we can make the social injustice of malnutrition go down in history," said Tracey Ullman, Ambassador of Power of Nutrition, at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that following more than 5,000 actions calling on the UK to improve the quality of maternal and child nutrition, the government announced funding for a Power of Nutrition project that will reach 5 million women and children with nutritional problems.
To one of the most frequently asked questions on their website, which read "How can you be sure that extreme poverty will be eradicated?",
The Global citizen responded as follows: "This will be a long and difficult road - sometimes we will stumble and fail.
But as with the once great civil rights movements and the fight against apartheid, we will succeed because together we are stronger.
Janet Jackson, the Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B, Janelle Monée are among the stars performing at this year's New York event, hosted by Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
