The U.S. ambassador accuses China of "harassing" propaganda ads.
A week after an official Chinese newspaper posted a four-page ad in a U.S. daily praising the mutual benefits of U.S.-Chinese trade, the U.S. ambassador to China accused Beijing of using the U.S. press to spread propaganda.
U.S. President Donald Trump last Wednesday referred to China Daily's paid addendum to the Des Moines Register, the most popular newspaper in the state of Iowa, accusing China of trying to meddle in the U.S. Congressional election on November 6, China denies this allegation.
Trump's allegation that Beijing tried to interfere in the U.S. election confirmed what U.S. officials told Reuters that this was a new stage in Washington's escalating campaign to pressure China.
While it is normal for foreign governments to post advertisements promoting trade with their countries, Beijing and Washington are currently escalating a trade war that has led to increased tariffs on reciprocal imports.
China's retaliatory tariffs at the start of the trade war were to affect exporters in states like Iowa that supported Trump's Republican Party, Chinese and American experts said.
Terry Branstad, the U.S. ambassador to China and former long-time governor of Iowa, the chief exporter of agricultural products to China, said Beijing had done harm to U.S. workers, farmers, and entrepreneurs.
Branstad stated in an article in the Sunday edition of the Des Moines Register that China "now with doubled force begins harassment by placing propaganda ads in our own free press."
"In its propaganda, the Chinese government benefits from a respected American tradition of free speech and free press by placing paid advertising on the Des Moines Register," Branstad wrote.
But there will be no dissenting voices in the Beijing street kiosk and no real reflection of the divergent opinions that the Chinese may have about China's worrying economic direction, given that the media are under the strong control of the Chinese Communist Party," he wrote.
He added that "one of China's best-known newspapers refused to publish" his article, though he did not say which newspaper.
