The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet to compete with Google and Facebook platforms.
Tim Berners-Lee, the creator of the World Wide Web, launches a startup to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google platforms.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company that builds on an open source platform, Solid, owned by Berners-Lee.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and what people have access to specific information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the goal of creating Inrupt was "world domination."
"We have to do it now," he said, referring to the startup.
"A historic moment has come."
The application uses Solid platform technology to allow people to create their own "online store with personal data" or otherwise POD.
It can include contact lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library, and other personal and professional tools.
It's like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify available in one browser at the same time.
A unique feature of an online store with personal information is that it is entirely up to the user who has access to what information.
The company calls it "personal empowerment through data."
According to the company's CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is to provide resources, processes, and relevant skills to help make Solid's platform accessible to all people.
Currently, the company includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers employed to work on the project, and a volunteer developer community.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world were able to create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said that he and his team are not talking to "Facebook and Google about whether to make a total change that will turn all their business models upside down overnight.
"They don't ask for permission."
In a Medium post published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that "Inrupt's mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on the Solid platform."
In 1994, Berners-Lee changed the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Berners-Lee has been a major contributor to the net neutrality debate in recent months.
With Inrupt Berners-Lee, he will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely excited to be thinking about the next era in network development," added Berners-Lee.
