The memory of the only clergyman of the Church of England, who was awarded the Victoria Cross during World War I, was celebrated 100 years later in his hometown.
Lt. Col. Bernard Vann was decorated on 29 September 1918 for his assault on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a sniper four days later, never finding out that he had been awarded the highest British military order.
On Saturday, his two grandchildren unveiled a memorial stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Vann, said that the unveiling of the stone exactly on the centenary of his grandfather's decoration was "uniquely symbolic".
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918 Lt. Col. Vann led his battalion through the Canal Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy fire from field guns and machine guns."
He then hurried to the line of fire and with "the greatest courage" led her forward, then single-handedly launched an attack on the field division post, rendering three of them incapacitated.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann (72 years old) said his grandfather's actions were "something I could never live up to, but something humble at the same time."
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, laid a wreath after the end of a parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Vann said he felt "very honored to take part in the parade" and added that "the courage of a true hero is manifested in the support he receives from many people."
