New German warship delayed again
The newest frigate of the German Navy should be commissioned in 2014 to replace the aging Cold War war-era warships, but this will not happen until at least next year due to faulty layouts and rising costs at an alarming rate, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the main ship of the new Baden-Wuertemberg-class frigate, was postponed to the first half of 2019, the newspaper Die Zeit reported, citing the words of a military spokesman.
The ship should have been included in the Navy in 2014, but as a result of problems that arose after delivery, it was necessary to make changes to this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class units ordered by the Navy in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
Of course, they will be equipped with a powerful cannon, a number of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as technological solutions that prevent detection, ensuring, among others, reduction of radar, infrared and acoustic footprints.
Other important features include longer intervals between maintenance - operating new frigates should be possible for up to two years away from home ports.
Constant delays, however, mean that these modern warships, which are supposed to allow Germany to respond to situations abroad, will be obsolete by the time the service begins, Die Zeit notes.
The unfortunate F125 frigate made headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy returned the ship to the shipyard after delivery.
Little was known about the reasons behind the return, but German media reported a number of key "software and hardware bugs" that made the ship useless in a combat mission.
Software flaws were particularly important, as the Baden-Wuertemberg class ships were to be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which is half the size of the older Bremen class frigates.
It also proved that the ship is far too heavy, which reduces its performance and limits the ability of the Navy to carry out future upgrades.
The Rheinland-Pfalz, weighing 7,000 tons, is believed to be twice as heavy as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to faulty equipment, the cost of the entire project – including crew training – also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached a staggering EUR 3.1 billion (US$3.6 billion), while the initial cost was EUR 2.2 billion.
Problems with putting the new frigates into service are of particular importance in light of recent warnings that the strength of the German naval fleet is shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Parliament's defence committee, admitted that the navy was "end of ships capable of using".
He also said that the problem grew over time due to the decommissioning of old vessels without the provision of replacement ships.
