National Trust eavesdrops on secret bat lives
New research conducted on the Scottish Highlands estate is intended to show how bats use the landscape to get food.
The results of the study are expected to shed new light on the behaviour of these exceptional flying mammals and help guide future efforts to protect them.
The research, led by researchers from the National Trust for Scotland, will involve common and minor dwarfs, as well as brown long-eared bats and bats from the redhead nocturnal family at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be deployed at key locations around the property to keep track of bat activity throughout the day.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field tests using portable detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all recordings is aimed at determining the frequency of signals sent by bats and how individual species behave.
A habitat map and report will then be developed to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour on a landscape scale.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor at NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help identify the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow formation, as well as the best ways to maintain forest land for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development works that have an impact on splinters and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting installations can also pose a threat, as can fly adhesives and some chemicals used in building materials and even domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to night hunting habits, their ears are more helpful than their eyes in catching prey.
They use a complex echolocation technique to search for worms and obstacles in their path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
It consists of ten trained experts who regularly carry out surveys, checks on bogs, and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even established Scotland's first and only dedicated bat reserve on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
David Thompson, the estate manager, says it is the perfect territory for bats.
"Threave has a great area for bats," he said.
"We have old buildings, lots of old trees and excellent habitats.
However, there are still many unknowns about bats, and the work we do here and in other estates will help us better understand what they need to grow."
It emphasises the importance of control for bats before undertaking maintenance work on the estates, as the inadvertent destruction of one splinter can kill up to 400 females and young, which can lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are under protection – it is illegal to kill, harass, or disturb them, as well as destroy their splinters.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish officer of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to provide assistance.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats, and for many species, we don't even know how their populations are doing."
