According to the court document, both of these charges are punishable by death.
A few weeks after the attack, the federal jury presented Saipov with an indictment covering 22 positions, including eight counts of murder as part of an illegal activity – a procedure usually used by federal prosecutors in organized crime cases – and a charge of violence and destruction of motor vehicles.
According to prosecutors, organizing the attack required "solid planning and rethinking." The way in which Saipov carried it out, they described it as "monstrous, cruel and immoral."
"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov has brought harm, harm and loss to Diego Enrique Angelini's family and friends, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hern Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucca," states the notification of intent.
Five of the victims were Argentine nationals who stayed in New York touristy.
The last time a death penalty was filed in the South District of New York was ten years ago.
Accused Khalid Barnes was found guilty of the murder of two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The death penalty as a result of a federal case was last performed in New York City in 1953 on Julius and Ethel Rosenbergs. The marriage was lost after two years earlier they were found guilty of conspiracy and espionage for the Soviet Union during the Cold War.
Both Rosenbergs were executed in an electric chair on June 19, 1953.
