What benefits can the economic war between the United States and China bring to Beijing
The salvos starting the economic war between the U.S. and China were stunning and although the battle is still ongoing, in the long run the conflict between these countries may be beneficial to Beijing, experts say.
The first warning was issued this year by the President of the United States, Donald Trump, imposing tariffs on China's key export goods, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week after the introduction of new tariffs on $200 billion worth of goods (150 billion pounds), which resulted in the taxation of half of all goods entering the U.S. from China.
Each time Beijing reciprocated in nature, recently raising tariffs on $60 billion worth of American goods from five to ten percent.
China is determined to respond to every U.S. strike, and it does not look like the second economy in the world is about to give way.
Forcing Washington to withdraw means accepting the demands, but a public leaning of its head before the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
According to experts, however, if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressure from the trade war with the US could strengthen China in the long run, reducing the relationship between the two economies.
"The fact that a quick political decision made in Washington or Beijing could create conditions for economic chaos in one of the countries is in fact far more dangerous than observers have admitted so far," said Abigail Grace, a researcher on Asia at the Center for New American Security think tank.
According to the foreign minister, Syria is "ready" for the return of refugees
The government claims that Syria is ready for the voluntary return of refugees, and asks for help in rebuilding a country ruined as a result of more than seven years of war.
In his speech before the UN General Assembly, Syria's foreign minister, Walid al-Moualem, stated that conditions in the country were improving.
"The situation in our area is now more stable and secure thanks to the progress in combating terrorism," he said.
In an effort to restore normality, the government is constantly rebuilding areas destroyed by terrorists.
All conditions have already been met so that refugees who have had to leave the country because of terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their daily lives and livelihoods can voluntarily return to it.
According to UN estimates, more than 5.5 million people have left Syria since the war began in 2011.
Another six million people who still live there need humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would be happy to accept help in rebuilding the devastated country.
However, he stressed that he would not accept aid conditional on conditions or offered by countries that sponsored the rebellion.
Europe seals victory at the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team won the 2018 Ryder Cup, beating the U.S. team with a score of 16.5 to 10.5 at the Le Golf National field in the Paris suburbs.
On European soil, the United States has lost for the sixth time in a row and has not won the Ryder Cup in Europe since 1993.
Europe regained the trophy when, under the leadership of the Danish captain, Thomas Bjorn, it scored 14.5 points that were needed to defeat the US.
American star Phil Mickelson, who was not doing well for most of the tournament, hit the ball from the stand straight into the water at the 16th hole of PAR3, thus giving the match to Francesc Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari shined through all the rounds and became one of four players who, since 1979, when this tournament was first held in its current format, managed to score 5-0-0.
American Jordan Spieth was eliminated with a score of 5&4 by Europe's lowest ranked player, Thorbjorn Olesen of Denmark.
Dustin Johnson, who holds the highest position in the world rankings, lost by two holes before the last hole against Englishman Ian Poulter, for whom it may have been the last Ryder Cup tournament.
The European with the highest number of victories in the Ryder Cup was the Spaniard Sergio Garcia, who had already taken part in eight such tournaments and scored 25.5 career points.
"I don't usually cry, but today I can't help myself.
It's been a tough year.
I am very grateful to Thomas for believing in me and choosing me.
I'm very happy to have the cup back.
It's a success for the whole team and I'm glad I could help," said the touched Garcia after the team's victory from Europe.
He hands over the baton to his compatriot, John Rahm, who defeated American golf legend Tiger Woods on Sunday with a 2&1 score.
"I feel incredible pride in winning against Tiger Woods. I grew up watching his game," said 23-year-old Rahm.
Woods lost all the matches in France and now has a 13-21-3 score in the Ryder Cup.
This is an unprecedented statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 major titles and has only given way to Jack Nicklaus.
The U.S. team had trouble finding a treadmill all weekend, except for Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played at a really high level throughout the tournament.
After a disappointing performance of the American lineup, his captain, Jim Furyk, said, "I'm proud of the guys, they fought.
At some point this morning we pressed some Europeans.
We withdrew.
Hats off in front of Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All of his 12 players played really well.
Together with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Commission, we will find a way to move forward.
I love these 12 guys, and I'm proud to be their captain.
I am full of admiration for my opponents.
They played a lot better than us."
Information about the bulwark – in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota, the density of plankton decreases
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decrease in plankton densities in some parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, the presence of a mottled bloom has been reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte, and Collier counties, suggesting that its density is decreasing.
It stretches for approximately 209 kilometres of coastline, from the north of Pinellas County to the south of Lee County.
The blooms can be encountered about 16 kilometers off the coast of Hillsborough County, but compared to the previous week in a smaller number of places.
The bloom was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, there was an average concentration of plankton off the coast and in the waters of Pinellas County, low to medium off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high in Manatee County, natural to high off the coast and in the waters of Sarasota County, natural to medium in Charlotte County, natural to high off the coast and in the waters of Lee County, and low to low in Collier County.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Last week, however, they were not reported in northwest Florida.
